00:23:20,233 --> 00:23:22,469
All right.

262
00:23:24,008 --> 00:23:25,342
Who chooses the music?

263
00:23:25,352 --> 00:23:26,814
I'm sorry?

264
00:23:26,824 --> 00:23:28,190
I'm assuming it's not the residents.

265
00:23:28,200 --> 00:23:31,345
I don't see any of them
singing along.

266
00:23:31,401 --> 00:23:34,910
Yeah, well. You know the rooms on the regular
floors all have their own stereo systems

267
00:23:34,920 --> 00:23:37,054
so the patients can listen
to whatever they like.

268
00:23:37,064 --> 00:23:39,064
How kind.

269
00:23:40,008 --> 00:23:43,294
Now, we don't admit anyone
during the month of December,

270
00:23:43,304 --> 00:23:45,279
so Mrs. Andersson will
have to wait till January

271
00:23:45,289 --> 00:23:47,166
to make the big move.

272
00:23:47,176 --> 00:23:51,551
Just December, Christmas, you know, too
many emotional pitfalls.

273
00:23:51,561 --> 00:23:53,214
- Right.
- Sorry to interrupt, Madeleine.

274
00:23:53,224 --> 00:23:54,942
I'm looking for those documents
on Aubrey Burke.

275
00:23:54,952 --> 00:23:56,510
Sure. Go ahead.

276
00:23:56,520 --> 00:23:59,550
Mr. Andersson, this is Kristy,
our new managing nurse.

277
00:23:59,560 --> 00:24:01,791
Against some people's
better judgment.

278
00:24:01,801 --> 00:24:03,801
Now, now.

279
00:24:03,816 --> 00:24:05,887
Mr. Andersson is here about his wife,
Mrs. Andersson,

280
00:24:05,897 --> 00:24:07,326
who will be joining us in January.

281
00:24:07,336 --> 00:24:08,446
- Hi, there.
- Hi.

282
00:24:08,456 --> 00:24:09,535
We also have a policy,

283
00:24:09,545 --> 00:24:11,038
which I'm sure you saw
in the brochure,

284
00:24:11,048 --> 00:24:12,894
that our new residents
are not allowed visitors

285
00:24:12,904 --> 00:24:14,910
or receiving phone calls
during the first 30 days,

286
00:24:14,920 --> 00:24:16,766
just to give them a chance to settle in.

287
00:24:16,776 --> 00:24:18,776
What sort of visitors?

288
00:24:21,928 --> 00:24:24,563
Everyone. Even close relatives.

289
00:24:24,585 --> 00:24:26,078
I couldn't just leave her here.

290
00:24:26,088 --> 00:24:28,319
We understand,
it is very difficult

291
00:24:28,329 --> 00:24:31,007
to leave a loved one
in a new environment for so long,

292
00:24:31,017 --> 00:24:34,270
but most people need
that time to settle in.

293
00:24:34,280 --> 00:24:36,030
Before we had this rule in place,

294
00:24:36,040 --> 00:24:37,694
residents would forget
again and again

295
00:24:37,704 --> 00:24:39,166
why they were being left here.

296
00:24:39,176 --> 00:24:40,318
Whereas we find,

297
00:24:40,328 --> 00:24:42,942
you give them the month
to settle in,

298
00:24:42,952 --> 00:24:45,022
and they're happy as clams.

299
00:24:45,032 --> 00:24:50,398
And after that, a little visit home
every now and then, perfectly fine.

300
00:24:50,408 --> 00:24:53,638
We'll take good care
of her, I promise.

301
00:24:56,809 --> 00:24:59,039
- Knock-knock.
- Oh, no! Not again.

302
00:24:59,049 --> 00:25:02,048
Knock-knock. Boo.

303
00:25:09,801 --> 00:25:11,838
- She's bringing two babies.
- Two babies?

304
00:25:11,848 --> 00:25:14,993
She's got a new baby,
four months old.

305
00:27:56,425 --> 00:27:58,425
Smells good.

306
00:28:00,201 --> 00:28:03,647
I was going to go for a ski,
but I thought I shouldn't chance it,

307
00:28:03,657 --> 00:28:05,983
what with the Alzheimer's and all.

308
00:28:05,993 --> 00:28:07,199
Why didn't you wake me?

309
00:28:07,209 --> 00:28:09,209
What are these, Grant?

310
00:28:17,961 --> 00:28:20,639
Those are the documents
you're supposed to sign

311
00:28:20,649 --> 00:28:23,455
if you decide to go to Meadowlake.

312
00:28:23,465 --> 00:28:25,440
That is exactly
what I have decided.

313
00:28:25,450 --> 00:28:28,223
You were to go and sign these
and leave them there.

314
00:28:28,233 --> 00:28:32,143
I wouldn't be allowed
to visit you for 30 days.

315
00:28:38,601 --> 00:28:44,003
30 days isn't such a long time
after 44 years.

316
00:28:44,073 --> 00:28:46,708
I don't think I like the place.

317
00:28:50,024 --> 00:28:55,426
I don't think we should be looking
for something we like, Grant.

318
00:28:55,497 --> 00:28:58,472
I don't think we'll ever find that.

319
00:28:59,784 --> 00:29:02,431
I think all we can aspire
to in this situation

320
00:29:02,441 --> 00:29:04,897
is a little bit of grace.

321
00:29:47,273 --> 00:29:50,758
I suppose I'll be
dressed up all the time.

322
00:29:51,849 --> 00:29:56,421
It will be sort of like... in a hotel.

323
00:30:00,682 --> 00:30:01,984
How do I look?

324
00:30:01,994 --> 00:30:03,167
Just like always.

325
00:30:03,177 --> 00:30:04,863
Just as you've always looked.

326
00:30:04,873 --> 00:30:06,873
And how does that look?

327
00:30:09,130 --> 00:30:11,130
Direct and vague...

328
00:30:12,457 --> 00:30:14,629
sweet and ironic.

329
00:30:20,264 --> 00:30:22,264
Is that how I look?

330
00:30:34,537 --> 00:30:36,708
Oh. Remember?

331
00:30:39,369 --> 00:30:41,215
Surprised, Grant?

332
00:30:41,225 --> 00:30:42,687
No, I'm not surprised.

333
00:30:42,697 --> 00:30:46,013
I'm just grateful
you can remember that.

334
00:30:46,089 --> 00:30:48,959
I'm not all gone, Grant. Just...

335
00:30:49,033 --> 00:30:51,270
going...

336
00:30:54,058 --> 00:30:57,203
There are things
I wish would go away.

337
00:30:58,409 --> 00:31:03,362
But won't. You know.
Things we don't talk about.

338
00:31:08,489 --> 00:31:11,010
You never left me.

339
00:31:11,082 --> 00:31:12,447
You still made love to me,

340
00:31:12,457 --> 00:31:15,602
despite disturbing demands elsewhere.

341
00:31:19,018 --> 00:31:24,069
But all those sandals, Grant.
All those bare female toes.

342
00:31:26,346 --> 00:31:30,016
What could you do but be a part of the time
you were a part of?

343
00:31:30,026 --> 00:31:32,328
All those pretty girls.

344
00:31:32,394 --> 00:31:36,644
Didn't seem like anyone
was willing to be left out.

345
00:31:37,033 --> 00:31:38,463
I think you did all right,

346
00:31:38,473 --> 00:31:42,816
compared to some
of your colleagues.

347
00:31:42,889 --> 00:31:45,224
Those who left their wives.

348
00:31:47,401 --> 00:31:50,886
And the women who
wouldn't put up with it.

349
00:31:53,193 --> 00:31:57,896
I think people are too demanding.

350
00:31:57,962 --> 00:32:01,247
People want to be in love
every single day.

351
00:32:01,257 --> 00:32:05,698
What a liability. And then that silly girl.

352
00:32:05,770 --> 00:32:07,895
That silly girl Veronica.

353
00:32:08,713 --> 00:32:11,359
Girls that age
are always going around

354
00:32:11,369 --> 00:32:14,684
saying they're going
to kill themselves.

355
00:32:14,697 --> 00:32:16,697
But that was that.

356
00:32:18,249 --> 00:32:19,712
Promised me a new life.

357
00:32:19,722 --> 00:32:21,826
We moved out here,

358
00:32:21,898 --> 00:32:25,159
that is exactly what you gave me.

359
00:32:27,434 --> 00:32:29,247
How long ago was that?

360
00:32:29,257 --> 00:32:32,160
20 years.

361
00:32:36,170 --> 00:32:38,170
God, that's shocking.

362
00:32:39,946 --> 00:32:44,223
So you see, I'm going...

363
00:32:44,298 --> 00:32:46,785
but I'm not gone.

364
00:33:14,410 --> 00:33:16,614
- Fiona.
- Grant.

365
00:33:19,626 --> 00:33:21,626
Don't go.

366
00:33:22,985 --> 00:33:24,992
That's what is happening, Grant.

367
00:33:25,002 --> 00:33:27,968
It's happening... right now.

368
00:33:56,969 --> 00:33:58,969
Fiona.

369
00:34:00,009 --> 00:34:01,888
Hello. I'm checking in today.

370
00:34:01,898 --> 00:34:03,679
My name is Fiona Andersson.

371
00:34:03,689 --> 00:34:04,895
Yes, Mrs. Andersson.

372
00:34:04,905 --> 00:34:06,752
We have your room
all ready for you.

373
00:34:06,762 --> 00:34:08,320
- Perfect.
- We'll have our supervisor,

374
00:34:08,330 --> 00:34:09,472
Mrs. Montpelier, show you.

375
00:34:09,482 --> 00:34:11,840
I'll go fetch her. She's expecting you.

376
00:34:11,850 --> 00:34:13,850
Thank you.

377
00:34:14,058 --> 00:34:16,058
Fiona.

378
00:34:16,138 --> 00:34:17,600
Grant.

379
00:34:17,610 --> 00:34:19,232
I can't go away from you like this.

380
00:34:19,242 --> 00:34:23,945
We had nothing
to tie us down, Grant.

381
00:34:24,010 --> 00:34:26,752
You could have just driven away
and forsaken me.

382
00:34:26,762 --> 00:34:29,064
But you didn't.

383
00:34:30,602 --> 00:34:32,602
I thank you for that.

384
00:34:37,066 --> 00:34:38,976
- Mrs. Andersson.
- Oh, hello.

385
00:34:38,986 --> 00:34:41,024
- How do you do? I'm Madeleine.
- Hello.

386
00:34:41,034 --> 00:34:42,625
Should I give you two a moment?

387
00:34:42,635 --> 00:34:44,544
- No, thank you.
- Yes, please.

388
00:34:44,554 --> 00:34:46,336
All right, then, well,
we'll get you settled in your room,

389
00:34:46,346 --> 00:34:48,320
and then I'd like to give you
a tour of the facility.

390
00:34:48,330 --> 00:34:52,325
- That'd be lovely. Thank you.
- Right this way.

391
00:34:56,905 --> 00:35:01,070
So, as you can see,
we get a lot of natural light.

392
00:35:01,674 --> 00:35:03,976
Here we go.

393
00:35:11,114 --> 00:35:14,278
Yes. This'll do just fine.

394
00:35:14,346 --> 00:35:16,704
Good. I'm so glad
you like it. Now, is...

395
00:35:16,714 --> 00:35:18,368
is this all you brought
with you today?

396
00:35:18,378 --> 00:35:21,268
- For now.
- We'll see how it goes.

397
00:35:22,122 --> 00:35:25,951
Well, if you need any help arranging things,
you just let me know.

398
00:35:25,961 --> 00:35:29,093
Thank you, Mrs. Montpelier.

399
00:35:29,163 --> 00:35:32,544
Now, if you wouldn't mind, I'd like to say
good-bye to my husband.

400
00:35:32,554 --> 00:35:36,928
We haven't been apart for a month
for the last 44 years.

401
00:35:36,938 --> 00:35:38,176
It could be quite something.

402
00:35:38,186 --> 00:35:40,186
Okay.

403
00:35:46,506 --> 00:35:48,506
Please, Fiona.

404
00:35:51,626 --> 00:35:53,665
Grant.

405
00:35:53,738 --> 00:35:56,258
Fiona...

406
00:35:56,330 --> 00:35:58,370
You know what I'd like?

407
00:36:01,898 --> 00:36:03,584
I'd like to make love,

408
00:36:03,594 --> 00:36:06,693
and then I'd like you to go.

409
00:36:06,763 --> 00:36:08,128
Because I need to stay here,

410
00:36:08,138 --> 00:36:09,984
and if you make it hard for me,

411
00:36:09,994 --> 00:36:12,969
I might cry so hard
I'll never stop.

412
00:36:44,266 --> 00:36:46,266
Go now.

413
00:36:48,299 --> 00:36:50,299
Go now.

414
