00:37:56,842 --> 00:37:58,752
I can come find you
in the dining room?

427
00:37:58,762 --> 00:38:00,802
Sure. That's fine.

428
00:38:02,730 --> 00:38:05,824
"The red roof lights
revolved in the afternoon sun,

429
00:38:05,834 --> 00:38:09,319
and even the dogs were
temporarily quiet."

430
00:38:21,994 --> 00:38:25,857
Hi, there, Mr. Andersson.
Now, how can I help you?

431
00:38:25,867 --> 00:38:27,777
Going down the center
of the dining room...

432
00:38:27,787 --> 00:38:30,753
That's Frank. He used to be the play-by-play
guy for the Winnipeg Jets.

433
00:38:30,763 --> 00:38:32,763
- Really?
- Yeah.

434
00:38:32,811 --> 00:38:35,649
He loved his job too much to retire.

435
00:38:35,659 --> 00:38:38,039
Frank's on the second floor.

436
00:38:41,355 --> 00:38:48,839
I just... My wife has always been
sort of a different sort of person.

437
00:38:48,907 --> 00:38:53,504
I've been told that Alzheimer's can't be
confirmed until after...

438
00:38:53,514 --> 00:38:55,751
And on our way here today,

439
00:38:55,819 --> 00:38:57,537
we passed this conservation area

440
00:38:57,547 --> 00:39:00,613
where we went
for a walk last spring.

441
00:39:00,683 --> 00:39:02,881
And there were these gorgeous flowers.
The skunk lilies.

442
00:39:02,891 --> 00:39:04,737
Oh, those are
beautiful, aren't they?

443
00:39:04,747 --> 00:39:07,520
Yes, they really made
an impression, see?

444
00:39:07,530 --> 00:39:09,824
And even though the whole
place was covered in snow,

445
00:39:09,834 --> 00:39:12,387
she said, "Oh, remember?"

446
00:39:13,931 --> 00:39:16,960
Now, that was...
that was... quite recently.

447
00:39:16,970 --> 00:39:20,257
And isn't the short-term memory
the thing that goes first?

448
00:39:20,267 --> 00:39:24,576
Well, yeah, but not all at once.

449
00:39:24,651 --> 00:39:26,081
And what's comforting

450
00:39:26,091 --> 00:39:31,276
is the long-term memory sometimes
stays for quite a long time.

451
00:39:31,371 --> 00:39:34,176
Yeah, her long-term memory
seems quite intact.

452
00:39:34,186 --> 00:39:37,665
But when she mentioned that,
about the skunk lilies,

453
00:39:37,675 --> 00:39:40,417
it was all I could do not
to turn the truck around.

454
00:39:40,427 --> 00:39:46,722
What if this is just her
just being herself?

455
00:39:46,795 --> 00:39:48,966
She's far too young to...

456
00:39:50,506 --> 00:39:52,288
She is young.

457
00:39:52,298 --> 00:39:55,016
And it is hard.

458
00:39:55,083 --> 00:39:57,504
No doubt about that.

459
00:39:57,578 --> 00:39:59,958
A month is a real long time.

460
00:40:02,187 --> 00:40:05,377
I mean, between you and me,
I don't know about the policy myself.

461
00:40:05,387 --> 00:40:08,384
I think it makes it easier for the staff
is what I think.

462
00:40:08,394 --> 00:40:12,355
Look. I'll give you my pager number.

463
00:40:13,803 --> 00:40:15,329
You can call me
whenever you want.

464
00:40:15,339 --> 00:40:19,164
You can call me every day
if you feel like it.

465
00:40:21,163 --> 00:40:23,367
I don't know what to do.

466
00:40:25,099 --> 00:40:27,905
Mr. Andersson,
your wife wrote you this note,

467
00:40:27,915 --> 00:40:30,805
and she asked me to pass it along.

468
00:40:39,723 --> 00:40:41,723
Okay.

469
00:40:46,731 --> 00:40:48,870
Thank you so much.

